WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:08.640
Hi, everyone. Can everyone hear me? Yes? My name is Beatriz, featuring baby. I'm pregnant.

00:00:08.640 --> 00:00:16.360
And I came all the way from Brazil to share with you about a project that me and other

00:00:16.360 --> 00:00:21.600
people from the community that I'm part of did a translation of the R for Data Science

00:00:21.600 --> 00:00:31.520
book into Portuguese, which is the language that we speak in Brazil. And this is not working.

00:00:31.520 --> 00:00:39.680
So I guess most of you already know which book this is. It's the R for Data Science

00:00:39.680 --> 00:00:47.919
book. And this is a great book to learn about how to program in R and also about tidyverse

00:00:47.919 --> 00:00:54.959
in general. And this book is available online for free. So anyone can access the website

00:00:54.959 --> 00:01:01.520
and read the book and study. And also you can buy a printed version if you want. And

00:01:01.520 --> 00:01:07.599
in this talk, I want to talk to you about how we did a translation of this book into

00:01:07.599 --> 00:01:16.800
Portuguese and how we got people to contribute. So how did we translate the book into Portuguese?

00:01:16.800 --> 00:01:23.000
First of all, there is already a translation of the book in the first edition of the book

00:01:23.000 --> 00:01:30.760
that was translated in 2019 in Brazil, some years ago. But one of the problems is that

00:01:30.760 --> 00:01:37.279
it was available only on printed version. So you could not access it for free. And I'm

00:01:37.279 --> 00:01:45.639
not sure how much you all know about Brazil, but it's a country with a lot of income inequality.

00:01:45.639 --> 00:01:54.919
And the cost of this book now costs around 10% of the monthly minimum wage in Brazil.

00:01:54.919 --> 00:02:02.400
So for students, this is quite expensive. And this story about this translation starts

00:02:02.400 --> 00:02:10.039
back in 2019 in USAR. I had an opportunity to attend the conference with a diversity

00:02:10.039 --> 00:02:19.839
scholarship. And there I met a lot of people from the Latin community that Brazil speaks

00:02:19.839 --> 00:02:24.839
Portuguese. The whole other part of Latin America speaks Spanish. And we actually didn't

00:02:24.839 --> 00:02:31.720
connect. So that was a great experience. And Riva Quiroga, she was presenting about the

00:02:31.720 --> 00:02:38.440
translation of the book to Spanish. And she was presenting also about the development

00:02:38.440 --> 00:02:47.759
of a package called Atos, which had the translations of the datasets used in the book into Spanish.

00:02:47.759 --> 00:02:52.559
And that presentation inspired me a lot, because I didn't even know that it was possible to

00:02:52.559 --> 00:03:02.039
do a translation if you were not, like, a big publisher. And Riva and I got in touch.

00:03:02.039 --> 00:03:07.639
And in 2020, she said, okay, you cannot translate the book, because it was already translated.

00:03:07.639 --> 00:03:14.960
But what if we translate the datasets of the book? So you can use in tutorials, classes,

00:03:14.960 --> 00:03:20.960
and so on. So Datos got a sibling, which is called package

00:03:20.960 --> 00:03:32.759
Datos. And in English, it translates to datasets. And we got 11 volunteers to work on this project.

00:03:32.759 --> 00:03:39.119
Everyone that is on purple borders are people from R-Ladies groups. Not only from Brazil,

00:03:39.119 --> 00:03:47.559
but in other Latin American countries. So you see, it was not a project from R-Ladies,

00:03:47.559 --> 00:03:52.000
but a lot of people from R-Ladies were part of it.

00:03:52.000 --> 00:03:59.559
And now the package, it's available on CRAN. You can download and install it and use the

00:03:59.559 --> 00:04:07.960
datasets that you already know from the book, like Star Wars, Palmer Penguins, and New York

00:04:07.960 --> 00:04:17.640
City flights. And we did the translation of, like, the name of the variables, the categories

00:04:17.640 --> 00:04:25.480
and text variables, and also the help pages. All the help pages are also translated to

00:04:25.480 --> 00:04:32.839
Portuguese. I'm quite a GitHub user. And if you don't

00:04:32.839 --> 00:04:42.279
know what GitHub is, it's a platform that you can use to store your code and work collaboratively

00:04:42.279 --> 00:04:53.320
with other people that develops things. And this book is actually built on a GitHub repository.

00:04:53.399 --> 00:05:03.079
And during 2021, I noticed that there was some movement in the GitHub repo from the book,

00:05:03.079 --> 00:05:10.119
and that the authors were developing the second edition of the book. So that was our chance

00:05:10.119 --> 00:05:16.279
to maybe trying to have a translation of the book into Portuguese.

00:05:16.279 --> 00:05:25.679
So in this moment, some imposter syndrome thoughts came into my mind. Like, oh, you're

00:05:25.679 --> 00:05:31.640
just a PhD student. The authors of the book have a lot of things to worry about. They

00:05:31.640 --> 00:05:38.399
don't have time to worry about, like, translating stuff to Portuguese. Or there's a lot of people

00:05:38.399 --> 00:05:47.720
that might be more experienced than you. Excuse me. To do this translation.

00:05:47.720 --> 00:05:54.440
But after a while, I thought about a phrase that my mom always said. Which in Portuguese

00:05:54.440 --> 00:06:03.519
says... And the translation would be something like... If you don't ask, the answer will

00:06:03.519 --> 00:06:13.600
very rarely be no. Like, let's try. So inspired by my mom, I went on the GitHub

00:06:13.600 --> 00:06:20.959
repository and wrote an issue saying... Hey, Hadley, which is the first author of the book,

00:06:20.959 --> 00:06:26.320
it would be great if you have, like, the translation by the community of the second edition. I'm

00:06:26.320 --> 00:06:32.799
part of the team that did the translation of the package dados into Portuguese. Let

00:06:32.799 --> 00:06:39.200
us know if we can do it. And after a while, Hadley responded to me.

00:06:39.200 --> 00:06:45.160
He said that... Yeah. You cannot do the first edition. But maybe we can get an authorization

00:06:45.160 --> 00:06:54.839
to do the second edition. And eventually he said that... Already said yes. Yay! But we

00:06:54.839 --> 00:07:01.480
couldn't start that just yet. Because they were still writing the book. So we had to

00:07:01.480 --> 00:07:10.399
wait a bit. So during 2022, 2033, we had to wait until they finished the book. And

00:07:10.399 --> 00:07:17.079
this picture is from PositConf 2022. I had the opportunity to come here. And I said...

00:07:17.079 --> 00:07:21.799
Hey, Hadley, I'm a real person. I'm the person that wrote that issue. I'm really interested

00:07:21.799 --> 00:07:26.760
in doing that. It's not like a bot from GitHub or something.

00:07:26.760 --> 00:07:35.880
And in the middle of 2023, he said that the book was finished. And he asked if we wanted

00:07:35.880 --> 00:07:42.320
to ask already again. And then in September, we got the permission. Yay! So from September

00:07:42.320 --> 00:07:52.160
2023 until November 2024, we got more than 20 people working in this translation. Back

00:07:52.160 --> 00:08:00.720
then, I think, like, stuff was quite bad. It was not really good to be used. So people

00:08:00.720 --> 00:08:05.679
had to translate it. And we had, like, one person to translate the book and two people

00:08:05.679 --> 00:08:14.559
to review the translation. So... And these people are from, like, really different areas

00:08:14.559 --> 00:08:23.279
of knowledge. Not only all statisticians. And in the end of 2024, almost a year ago,

00:08:23.279 --> 00:08:32.880
we got the Portuguese version of the book online. So you can access it on pt.r4ds.hadley.nz.

00:08:32.880 --> 00:08:40.960
So it's an official domain from Hadley. And now everyone can access the second edition

00:08:40.960 --> 00:08:53.520
of the book for free and online. Yay! So how� so how we get so many people to contribute

00:08:53.520 --> 00:08:59.640
in this project. So there are three main things that I thought about when thinking about this

00:08:59.640 --> 00:09:08.000
talk. The first is widen our reach. I needed to find people to contribute. So the first

00:09:08.000 --> 00:09:13.599
thing is communities are a great way to find people. We found a lot of people in RLadies,

00:09:13.599 --> 00:09:22.000
as I said before. But also LatinR, which is the community for programmers from Latin America.

00:09:22.000 --> 00:09:31.440
Which has people that speak Portuguese, English, Spanish, Porto English, and so on. So it's

00:09:31.440 --> 00:09:40.000
really mixed. And also, like, local communities. So we found a lot of people on communities.

00:09:40.000 --> 00:09:45.760
And a lot of people also came from a call from volunteers on social media. You can see

00:09:45.760 --> 00:09:52.239
that blue sky is not here. Because most people use, like, LinkedIn and Instagram in Brazil.

00:09:52.239 --> 00:10:00.119
So we called for volunteers on the social media we use most there. And a lot of people

00:10:00.119 --> 00:10:08.840
that I never met before that were part of the translation team, they came from these

00:10:08.840 --> 00:10:14.280
posts on social media that other people shared. And the second thing that was important for

00:10:14.280 --> 00:10:23.159
us in this project was to show the path. As I said before, the book is stored in a GitHub

00:10:23.159 --> 00:10:30.440
repository. So we did a fork of that GitHub repository and did all the translations there.

00:10:30.440 --> 00:10:36.840
But it turns out a lot of people don't know how to use GitHub. So some people were interested

00:10:36.840 --> 00:10:45.719
in contributing, but they never used Git or GitHub before. Especially things like issues

00:10:45.719 --> 00:10:51.640
for requests and projects. Sometimes they knew how to, like, open up a repo and download

00:10:51.719 --> 00:10:57.479
it and close it. But they didn't know how to use these other features that we used a lot.

00:10:58.359 --> 00:11:06.599
So in the start of the project, I was doing one-on-one calls with the volunteers that

00:11:06.599 --> 00:11:15.000
needed help explaining to them how we could use Git and GitHub. But as the team grew,

00:11:15.000 --> 00:11:20.919
it was quite hard to keep it up with one-on-one calls all the time. So we started doing a

00:11:20.919 --> 00:11:27.880
translation guide, which is in a quarter book. So in this translation guide, we wrote things

00:11:27.880 --> 00:11:38.520
related to the translation itself. Some patterns that we were following. For example, Portuguese

00:11:38.520 --> 00:11:47.479
and Spanish are languages that have gender in all the words. Like, simple things that you speak

00:11:47.479 --> 00:11:57.559
in English and have no gender at all. Like, author. In Portuguese. So we had to think about

00:11:57.559 --> 00:12:04.359
how we would translate in a way that's more neutral. And not so, like, marked on gender.

00:12:04.359 --> 00:12:11.080
So we wrote all these ideas there. But we also wrote a bunch of chapters about what is Git and

00:12:11.080 --> 00:12:18.280
GitHub? How can you start, like, reviewing a chapter? And how you do a pull request and things

00:12:18.280 --> 00:12:25.000
like that. And that translation guide was, like, growing as the project was growing. Because new

00:12:25.640 --> 00:12:33.080
questions made me do, like, new contributions to this book. To this guide. And that helped us a

00:12:33.080 --> 00:12:39.320
lot. And I think this part was really important. Because if we didn't do, like, this

00:12:39.880 --> 00:12:46.760
capacitations, this guides, and one on one calls, a lot of people would be locked outside the

00:12:46.760 --> 00:12:52.359
translation project. And for a lot of people that were part of this, this was their first

00:12:52.359 --> 00:12:59.640
contribution to a community project or to open source or, like, using GitHub in general. So that

00:12:59.640 --> 00:13:06.359
was really important for us. And in this moment, I think it's really important to emphasize that

00:13:06.359 --> 00:13:13.239
we are standing in the shoulders of giants. So as I said before, the Spanish ‑‑ the

00:13:13.239 --> 00:13:18.679
Latin community, the Spanish people that are part of the Latin community, they already have done

00:13:18.679 --> 00:13:26.679
DR for data science in Spanish translation. So especially Riva, which is the leader of the

00:13:26.679 --> 00:13:35.080
translation, she helped us a lot with a lot of things that how they did the translation, the

00:13:35.080 --> 00:13:44.039
workflow, and what went wrong. So for us, it was really easier. Because we didn't have to

00:13:44.039 --> 00:13:48.599
repeat with the problems they had before. We didn't have to reinvent the wheel. And

00:13:50.679 --> 00:13:58.200
this is a community project. Not only for our Brazilian community, but it has a collaboration

00:13:58.200 --> 00:14:05.080
from the community in Latin America in general. So the third thing that I think is important in

00:14:05.080 --> 00:14:10.679
this kind of project, and it was important for our project, was to be patient. So you see that

00:14:10.679 --> 00:14:18.840
it was not quick. So the whole process from starting from Dados and Dados until the translation

00:14:18.840 --> 00:14:26.840
of the book took around four years. And the book has 30 chapters from small chapters to longer

00:14:26.840 --> 00:14:34.359
chapters. And we have around ‑‑ had around 30 volunteers from Dados and the book as well, from

00:14:34.359 --> 00:14:42.119
developing the translations of Dados and the book. And people involved are volunteers. So a lot of

00:14:42.119 --> 00:14:48.280
them were doing the contributions during their weekends, the time they could be with their

00:14:48.280 --> 00:14:54.679
families, and they chose to be there. So it was important for us to be a good experience for

00:14:54.679 --> 00:15:01.880
everyone. Sometimes people could stop responding or it took a long time. We just gave them

00:15:03.159 --> 00:15:10.039
gentle nudges, like, hey, are you still up to the ‑‑ are you still want to do this translation

00:15:10.039 --> 00:15:16.200
or this review? And if they said no, there was no problem, because we bring other people as

00:15:16.200 --> 00:15:21.479
reinforcements, because we had, like, this big pool of people that wanted to participate.

00:15:21.640 --> 00:15:29.880
And, as I said, it was important to be patient in this process, and it was really worth it, because

00:15:30.599 --> 00:15:38.359
two months ago ‑‑ no, some weeks ago, I was in a conference in Brazil, and I was in an effort of

00:15:38.359 --> 00:15:44.039
sharing about the book, because some people that are not part of the community still don't know

00:15:44.039 --> 00:15:51.239
about the book. And a lot of people thanked me in that moment, because ‑‑ and I said, it's not a

00:15:51.239 --> 00:15:57.320
project that I did. It was, like, a lot of people involved. But they thanked us a lot, because now

00:15:57.320 --> 00:16:03.159
they can use the book, like, in classes, and I know some teachers on universities that are already

00:16:03.159 --> 00:16:13.000
using it. So it was totally worth it. And as I said, the book is being used in university courses

00:16:13.000 --> 00:16:19.559
and activities on R‑Ladies and other communities, and we also are doing R‑Ladies book club.

00:16:21.159 --> 00:16:28.440
And this book club actually started while the book was being translated. So we already had 16

00:16:28.440 --> 00:16:35.159
meetings. Each meeting is focused on a chapter, and we're planning to do the whole book, so

00:16:35.880 --> 00:16:41.799
all the meetings is also recorded on YouTube, so people, if they cannot attend the meeting

00:16:41.799 --> 00:16:50.359
in that time, they can watch after. And some of them had, like, 600 views, 300 views, 900 views,

00:16:50.359 --> 00:16:59.080
so a lot of people cannot attend in that time, but they can watch later. And, yeah. So this project

00:16:59.080 --> 00:17:05.239
was a community project, and I would like to give a big thanks to some people. First, the authors

00:17:05.239 --> 00:17:14.439
of the book. So the book is written by Hadley Wickham. So thank you, the writers of the book,

00:17:14.439 --> 00:17:20.199
for not only writing the book, but saying okay to the translation, and also Riley, the publisher,

00:17:20.199 --> 00:17:25.640
for saying okay for this translation as well. I would like to thank the volunteers in this project,

00:17:25.640 --> 00:17:34.199
like, all the 30 people involved. And also the communities. R‑Ladies, Latin R, especially Riva,

00:17:34.680 --> 00:17:42.680
and the local communities. And also Bianca and Ariana, because they did some arts that are in

00:17:42.680 --> 00:17:48.520
the slides, and they're also part of the translation project. And so thank you. If you have any

00:17:48.520 --> 00:17:56.199
questions, I'll be around the conference. And you can also send me an e‑mail. This QR code sends

00:17:56.280 --> 00:18:00.839
you to the presentation and also to the book. So thank you for listening to me.

00:18:00.839 --> 00:18:12.520
Thank you so much. We do have a couple of questions here. So how important is it to

00:18:12.520 --> 00:18:17.239
have an active leader in a project like this? It seems like a lot of effort from yourself,

00:18:17.239 --> 00:18:24.520
and how much of the work can be delegated? I think it's really important to have a person

00:18:24.520 --> 00:18:31.640
or some group of persons that are leading. Otherwise, people can be, like, with no focus.

00:18:33.079 --> 00:18:40.520
And I think there's some things that we could delegate, but it was a lot of effort from me to

00:18:40.520 --> 00:18:47.160
keep it up with everyone if they were still on board, if they want to join, if they needed help,

00:18:47.160 --> 00:18:52.839
and things like that. Yeah. They definitely ‑‑ we definitely need one leader in the project.

00:18:54.199 --> 00:18:59.079
I can say that from the participation in Our Ladies, I'm part of Our Ladies as well,

00:18:59.079 --> 00:19:03.560
and there we don't have, like, one leader. We have a lot of co‑organizers. And sometimes,

00:19:03.560 --> 00:19:12.359
like, a lot of people have other things going on, and it's hard to, like, have regular meetings and

00:19:12.359 --> 00:19:17.239
continue because you don't have, like, one person, like, say, hey, let's do it, because everyone's,

00:19:17.239 --> 00:19:23.239
like, oh, maybe other person can do it. And that doesn't work so well sometimes.

00:19:24.439 --> 00:19:29.880
Right. Totally. One other question here. Is the translation guide

00:19:29.880 --> 00:19:36.119
Cordo book or some lessons learned or tips from offering a translation guide,

00:19:36.119 --> 00:19:41.000
is it available in English? Or is the original available online still?

00:19:41.959 --> 00:19:47.319
It's only available in Portuguese, because we only did in Portuguese. Yeah. We only have it

00:19:47.319 --> 00:19:52.119
in Portuguese. Okay. But that is available online. Yeah. Yeah. It's available online. There's a link

00:19:52.119 --> 00:19:58.599
in the slides. Great. But I know there's other translation projects that also have some guides.

00:19:58.599 --> 00:20:06.119
Not sure if they have, like, these GitHub tutorials, but, yeah. There's also other

00:20:06.119 --> 00:20:14.199
translations, like, for Bazar or things that people have some guides for the translation.

00:20:15.479 --> 00:20:19.319
Amazing. Is there any tracking on the number of views of the book?

00:20:19.880 --> 00:20:26.520
Oh, no. No. I have to I didn't thought about, like, setting up, like, Google Analytics or

00:20:26.520 --> 00:20:31.000
something. And all the time someone asks me something like this, I'm, like, oh, I didn't

00:20:31.000 --> 00:20:35.719
think about setting up Google Analytics. So, I don't know how many people are accessing the book.

00:20:36.280 --> 00:20:44.439
Amazing. Thank you so much. Thank you.

